\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
The why, the when, and the how to impute: a practitioners’ guide to survey-to-su
rvey imputation of poverty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Paul Corral, Andres Ham, Leonardo Lucchetti, and Henry Stemmler
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The measurement and monitoring of poverty are central to assessing global
 development progress.
 For the World Bank, whose twin goals include ending extreme poverty, the
 ability to track poverty reduction is fundamental to measuring institutional
 effectiveness and guiding policy decisions.
 Yet a persistent challenge hampers this crucial task: the limited availability
 of recent, high-quality household survey data.
 This challenge is particularly acute in countries where poverty is concentrated
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DangJolliffeCarletto"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For instance, India, home to a significant share of the global poor, did
 not release official consumption survey data between 2011 and 2022.
 Similarly, Nigeria lacked household survey data for poverty monitoring
 between 2009 and 2018.
 These data gaps not only affect our understanding of poverty at the country
 level but can significantly impact global poverty estimates and our assessment
 of progress toward poverty reduction targets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Traditional poverty measurement relies on household surveys that collect
 detailed consumption or income data.
 These surveys represent substantial investments in both financial and human
 resources.
 They require extensive preparation, careful implementation, and place considera
ble burden on responding households, who must either maintain detailed consumpti
on diaries or participate in comprehensive recall interviews.
 The method of data collection itself can introduce significant biases into
 poverty estimates.
 For instance, consumption diaries – while theoretically more accurate –
 can lead to respondent fatigue and underreporting over time.
 Recall modules, on the other hand, may suffer from memory bias, with longer
 recall periods typically resulting in lower reported consumption.
 Research has shown that simply changing the recall period or the number
 of consumption items can lead to substantially different poverty estimates
 within the same population (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "beegle2012methods"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 These methodological challenges add another layer of complexity to the
 already demanding task of poverty measurement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The challenges of traditional poverty measurement become particularly acute
 during crises when standard survey operations are disrupted or impossible
 to conduct.
 Armed conflicts, natural disasters, health emergencies, and other humanitarian
 crises often prevent face-to-face household interviews precisely when poverty
 monitoring becomes most crucial.
 The COVID-19 pandemic provided a stark illustration of this challenge,
 as household survey efforts were halted globally at a time when understanding
 welfare impacts was most critical.
 Similar data collection constraints arise in conflict zones, where security
 concerns prevent enumerator access to households, or during natural disasters
 that displace populations and disrupt statistical operations.
 During such crises, policymakers and international organizations must resort
 to alternative methods for estimating poverty.
 Survey-to-survey imputation, often combined with rapid phone surveys or
 other alternative data collection methods, has emerged as a key tool for
 maintaining poverty monitoring during these challenging periods.
 However, these approaches come with their own limitations and potential
 biases that must be carefully considered.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For global monitoring see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mahler_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Global projections of poverty rely on GDP projections during the pandemic.
 The GDP projection for each country is used to shift the welfare distribution
 of a given country by the GDP per capita growth rate observed between year
 corresponding to the household survey collection and the desired year in
 the future.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Survey-to-survey (S2S) imputation has emerged as a methodological response
 to these data limitations.
 The approach builds upon techniques originally developed for small area
 estimation (SAE) in poverty mapping, pioneered by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jesko1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and further refined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 S2S imputation enables poverty estimation using surveys that lack direct
 welfare measures by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Developing a predictive model of household welfare using a survey with consumpti
on or income data (the "source" survey) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Applying this model to a different survey containing similar household character
istics but lacking direct welfare (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

target
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 survey)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Generating poverty estimates based on the predicted welfare distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While S2S and small area estimation share methodological foundations, they
 serve distinct purposes.
 Small area estimation, as developed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and advanced by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "molina2010small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, typically applies nationally estimated models to census data to generate
 precise poverty estimates for small geographic areas.
 In contrast, S2S focuses on predicting welfare in a separate survey, regardless
 of geographic disaggregation.
 One might view traditional poverty mapping as a special case of S2S where
 the target dataset are the different areas of the census and the primary
 goal is obtaining geographically disaggregated estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This handbook first examines the limitations and potential pitfalls of survey-to
-survey imputation through rigorous analysis of its fundamental assumptions.
 In these experiments, the focus is not on traditional concerns such as
 variable selection or model specification, but rather on the method's core
 limitations, particularly for measuring poverty across extended time periods
 or different populations.
 The analysis relies on simulated data to isolate and demonstrate specific
 mechanisms that can generate biased estimates.
 This approach allows for clear illustration of three critical findings:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Standard sampling bias-correction techniques, such as re-weighting to match
 population means, may be insufficient when source and target surveys differ
 fundamentally.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The method's tendency to replicate the welfare distribution of the source
 survey makes it unreliable for measuring changes in inequality.
 These insights are particularly relevant given the increasing reliance
 on survey-to-survey imputation to fill data gaps in poverty monitoring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Third, omitted variable bias will likely affect poverty predictions, particularl
y when imputing across time periods that include significant economic shocks
 or structural changes.
 This last finding has important implications for applications that use
 "fast-moving" variables to capture welfare changes, as these variables
 may introduce bias if they are correlated with unobserved factors that
 affect welfare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Through systematic examination of these limitations using simplified examples,
 the handbook provides practitioners with a framework for understanding
 when and why S2S methods may produce misleading results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because things with real world data tend to work somewhat differently than
 expected, the handbook then proceeds to validate imputation techniques
 leveraging the Peruvian data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The results here are of relevance since survey-to-survey imputation has
 become more prevalent in recent times to overcome data scarcity.
 One example is the multiple applications in India, where survey data useful
 for global poverty monitoring have not been released since 2011.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Survey-to-Survey Imputation in Action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Survey-to-survey imputation has become a widely used tool for poverty estimation
 when consumption or income data are unavailable.
 The World Bank's Survey of Well-being via Instant and Frequent Tracking
 (SWIFT) program represents a systematic application of this approach, combining
 S2S methods with rapid surveys to generate poverty estimates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Evidence from country applications has revealed both the potential and limitatio
ns of these methods.
 In Afghanistan, a 2015 implementation failed to capture significant changes
 in poverty rates when using a model trained on 2011 data (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "SwiftMethod"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Similar challenges have emerged in other contexts experiencing rapid economic
 transitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fundamental challenge lies in the method's core assumptions.
 S2S imputation assumes that model parameters remain stationary over time
 - meaning that any observed changes in poverty are solely attributable
 to changes in the model's covariates, rather than shifts in unobservable
 factors or changing returns to these covariates (Dang, Lanjouw and Serajuddin
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citebyear
key "dang2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This assumption becomes particularly tenuous in dynamic economic contexts.
 As 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "christiaensen2012small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 note, such assumptions may be especially problematic in rapidly growing
 economies like India, where structural economic changes can alter the relations
hip between poverty and its predictors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Researchers and practitioners have proposed various approaches to address
 these limitations.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "stifel2007tracking"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 advocate for including time-varying variables such as rainfall and prices
 to capture temporal changes.
 In response to experiences like Afghanistan, the SWIFT program has adapted
 its application of S2S by incorporating variables that track economic condition
s more directly 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SwiftMethod"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "SwiftMethod"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 emphasize, without updated training data to re-estimate model parameters,
 the risk of missing significant economic changes remains substantial, even
 with these additional variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effectiveness of S2S imputation across time has been subject to empirical
 validation across various contexts, revealing both its potential and limitation
s.
 While some studies report estimates within acceptable margins of error,
 others highlight significant discrepancies between predicted and observed
 poverty rates.
 These mixed results underscore the importance of careful consideration
 when applying S2S imputation across different temporal and economic contexts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bias of estimates obtained with data that correspond to very different
 time periods or data where the covariates are considerably different has
 mostly been studied using real world data.
 For example, Dang, Lanjouw and Serajuddin (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citebyear
key "dang2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) conduct experiments using the Household Expenditure and Income Survey
 and the Unemployment and Employment Survey in Jordan; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "stifel2007tracking"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 rely on survey data for Kenya to conduct experiments; Dang et al.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citebyear
key "dang2021poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) applies the method to several countries and note that estimates are well
 within margins of error.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The countries are: Ethiopia, Malawi, Nigeria, Tanzania, and Vietnam
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "christiaensen2012small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 undertakes an empirical validation of survey-to-survey imputation methods
 over time.
 The authors perform survey-to-survey imputation over time in scenarios
 where there is a comparable expenditure data which provides a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 estimate of poverty.
 The authors validate their approach using data for Vietnam and for China
 using rural household panel data.
 In Vietnam, the authors obtain a model using the 1992/93 data and predict
 poverty using the 1997/98 data.
 They note that the method works relatively well and depending on the covariates
 used, differences between predicted and observed poverty rates were on
 average 3.4 percentage points during a period where poverty fell by 23.2
 percentage points.
 For the Chinese regions where the method was tested, the authors also find
 that the methods work relatively well.
 However, depending on the model used differences between predicted and
 observed rates were considerable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Applications of survey to survey imputation have also made their way to
 global poverty monitoring.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As of this writing, every poverty number for India after 2011 is an imputation.
 These numbers are reported in the World Bank's Poverty and Inequality Platform
 with no warning to visitors on the origins of the numbers.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is mostly due to India's lack of recent survey data.
 The following case studies illustrate specific instances where S2S applications
 have found their way to the World Bank's global poverty numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
S2S in India
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
India's importance in global poverty measurement cannot be overstated.
 Its large population implies that even a slight shift in poverty in the
 country can make or break the World Bank's pledge on ending extreme poverty.
 Consequently, since 2011, the last time data was collected before 2022,
 there are at least 3 different studies which attempt to estimate a poverty
 rate for the country making use of survey-to-survey imputation (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "newhouse2019estimating,sinha2022poverty,edochie2022we"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 These papers obtain a welfare model constructed on the 2011 data and apply
 it to several more recent data which lack a welfare measure to obtain poverty
 predictions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2017, when the next expenditure survey for the country was supposed to
 be released it was scrapped due to concerns regarding its validity.
 There were leaks of the report, however, and these suggested that between
 2011 and 2017/18 consumption in the country had fallen by 3.7 percent.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "https://www.thehinducentre.com/the-arena/current-issues/article30265409.ece"
target "https://www.thehinducentre.com/the-arena/current-issues/article30265409.ece"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 While rural consumption fell by 8.8 percent, urban areas fared somewhat
 better and grew by 2 percent over the period.
 Given the lack of actual data to validate the leaked report and the fact
 that the survey was never 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

official
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the leaked report never fed into the World Bank's global poverty monitoring
 efforts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Various studies utilizing survey-to-survey (S2S) imputation have produced
 divergent estimates of poverty in India, raising questions about the robustness
 of such methods.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "newhouse2019estimating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 estimate a dramatic reduction in poverty, from 22.5 percent in 2011/12 to
 12.7 percent in 2014/15, suggesting poverty was nearly halved during this
 period.
 In contrast, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sinha2022poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provide a higher poverty estimate for 2015, ranging between 18.6 percent
 and 20.6 percent, while an earlier version of the same paper placed the
 figure at around 15 percent.
 Similarly, estimates for 2017/18 differ: the World Bank's Poverty and Shared
 Prosperity Report (PSPR) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "WorldBank2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "edochie2022we"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, provides estimates of poverty at 9.9 percent.
 However, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sinha2022poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 suggest the poverty rate for 2017 lies between 12.2 and 15.3 percent, with
 a previous version of their work estimating 13 to 14 percent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A common feature across these imputation exercises is their reliance on
 parameters derived from the 2011 National Sample Survey (NSS), despite
 significant changes in the Indian economy since then.
 This reliance has produced conflicting trends.
 For example, the imputation-based models suggest declining poverty and
 inequality, while data from a leaked, retracted 2017-18 report indicates
 a fall in rural consumption across all deciles of the welfare distribution,
 with higher declines among wealthier groups.
 This discrepancy underscores the limitations of imputation-based approaches
 when direct data is unavailable, leaving critical questions about the accuracy
 and reliability of poverty estimates unanswered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other authors have attempted to arrive at a poverty rate for India leading
 to a wide range of predictions, leaving many to wonder what in fact is
 the true poverty rate for the country.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See for example: 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lanjouw2024imputation,bhalla2022pandemic"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Additionally, a key question in these contexts is what meaning do the estimated
 standard errors for the imputations carry? In some instances, through some
 very elaborate statistical applications poverty numbers are presented with
 statements of precision that may be misleading.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
S2S in Afghanistan
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Afghanistan's 2023 poverty estimates, derived through survey-to-survey (S2S)
 imputation, illustrate the complexities of applying this methodology during
 periods of significant economic transition.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barriga2023updating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 trained their model using the 2019-2020 Expenditure and Labor Force Survey
 (IE-LFS), which reported a national poverty rate of 52.3 percent, and applied
 it to 2023 phone survey data to estimate updated poverty rates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The estimates indicate a decline in poverty to 48.3 percent in 2023, driven
 by reductions in rural poverty despite slight increases in urban areas.
 While these results are noteworthy, several methodological and contextual
 factors warrant caution.
 First, the reliance on phone survey data introduces challenges related
 to representativeness.
 The 2023 estimates were based on responses from households in the 2019-20
 IE-LFS with access to phones and who participated in the follow-up survey.
 Although weights were adjusted for socioeconomic characteristics such as
 region, urban/rural status, electricity access, and household assets, such
 adjustments may not fully address potential biases inherent in phone-based
 surveys.
 Experimental evidence (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Results_simdata"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) demonstrates the risks of bias when using S2S imputation with re-weighted
 data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, the model’s performance metrics raise questions about its predictive
 accuracy.
 Even on the original 2019-20 data used for estimation, model predictions
 deviated by nearly 1 percentage point, indicating potential violations
 of key assumptions (Table 4 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barriga2023updating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ).
 When applied to 2021 data, the model overestimated urban poverty by 1.7
 percentage points and rural poverty by 2.1 points, suggesting that the reported
 4-percentage-point reduction in 2023 could fall within a margin of error
 rather than representing a clear trend.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, broader economic indicators appear inconsistent with the reported
 decline in poverty.
 Between 2019 and 2023, Afghanistan faced significant economic challenges,
 including severe GDP contraction after administrative changes and U.S.
 military withdrawal, droughts exacerbating food insecurity, reductions
 in emergency food assistance, a locust outbreak affecting key agricultural
 areas,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "WFP2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and a doubling of unemployment rates.
 These factors collectively point to heightened vulnerabilities rather than
 improvements in welfare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The authors attribute the poverty reduction primarily to reduced conflict
 and lower food prices.
 However, the model does not directly account for conflict, leaving this
 explanation speculative.
 Any effects would need to operate indirectly through the model’s existing
 covariates, raising concerns about omitted variable bias that could compromise
 its predictions over time (see Annex 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ann_ovb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for further discussion and section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Omitted-Variables"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for simulation results).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additionally, the model’s reliance on consumption indicators, such as meat
 and egg consumption, introduces further uncertainty.
 Much of the welfare gains in rural areas stem from variables capturing
 these specific consumption patterns, which may be closely tied to conflict
 and other contextual factors.
 For instance, reported meat consumption increased by 30 percent and egg
 consumption doubled, with these variables contributing significantly to
 the estimated rise in real per capita consumption.
 Yet such trends seem incongruous with broader economic realities, underscoring
 the challenges in interpreting these results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In sum, Afghanistan’s 2023 poverty estimates highlight the difficulties
 of using S2S imputation during periods of economic upheaval.
 The case underscores the need for cautious interpretation of imputed results,
 particularly when data collection limitations, methodological assumptions,
 and contextual factors may influence the findings.
 Recognizing these complexities is critical to ensuring the reliability
 of poverty estimates in challenging contexts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Case of Zambia
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zambia’s gap in survey data between 2015 and 2022 presented a challenge
 for monitoring poverty trends.
 Compounding this challenge, the 2022 consumption data is not directly comparabl
e to 2015 data due to differences in survey design.
 While the 2015 survey used a fixed recall period for food consumption,
 the 2022 survey allowed respondents to choose different reference periods
 for reporting quantities and values of consumption.
 This variation in reporting likely undermines the comparability of the
 two datasets, complicating the construction of poverty trends 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "beegle2012methods"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To address this issue, the Zambia team employed survey-to-survey (S2S) imputatio
n to project the 2015 welfare aggregate onto the 2022 data.
 Using this approach, they estimate that international poverty ($2.15 2017
 USD PPP) increased by nearly 4 percentage points between 2015 and 2022,
 rising from 60.8 to 64.4 percent.
 At the same time, inequality, as measured by the Gini index, is predicted
 to have decreased from 55.9 to 51.5, and average consumption fell by 15 percent,
 from $2.97 (2017 PPP) to $2.53 (2017 PPP).
 While these results suggest a worsening of economic conditions, they also
 raise questions about the broader macroeconomic context.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the imputed estimates indicate declining welfare, Zambia’s GDP
 per capita in constant terms barely changed between 2015 and 2022, recovering
 to its pre-pandemic levels by 2022 and exceeding its 2018 peak by 2023.
 This divergence between household survey-based consumption estimates and
 national accounts data highlights a growing gap to national accounts that
 is not easily explained.
 Literature suggests such gaps may stem from underreporting of incomes in
 surveys 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ravallion2003measuring"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, although they tend to narrow as countries become wealthier 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "prydz2022disparities"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Given the point of the distribution where mean welfare falls on, a drop
 in Gini and an increase in poverty are not incongruous.
 However, if average consumption indeed fell and poverty increased, as the
 predictions suggest, it is unclear why all of a sudden the gap to national
 accounts would widen.
 If the GDP measure is accurate, then the drop in mean consumption, would
 suggest that consumption must have shifted to the richest population likely
 leading to increased inequality.
 On the other hand, if the predictions are correct, then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
how inequality also dropped while the overall economy remained relatively
 unchanged as noted by the GDP per capita measures.
 On the one hand, had a larger share of welfare accumulated at the top of
 the distribution, since GDP per capita has barely changed but mean consumption
 has decreased, inequality should have increased.
 On the other hand, if it would have accumulated at the bottom of the 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The comparable components of expenditure correspond to 33.7 percent of the
 2015 survey expenditure, but does not include food, and frequent non-food
 components.
 The comparable component consists mainly of health, a sub-set of education,
 clothing, financial services, durables, and housing.
 The last item, housing, corresponds to imputed rent.
 In urban areas, the comparable component suggests consumption has decreased
 in real terms.
 In rural areas there is no discernible change.
 The authors validate their results applying a method from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "deaton2003adjusted"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that relies on a comparable subset of the welfare aggregate and is aligned
 to that based on the imputation model.
 The authors also validate their model by imputing on the same data as the
 one used for the model.
 Their validations already point toward a slight upward bias in their model
 for urban areas, same for their Gini predictions, both likely driven by
 the residuals not meeting the model's assumptions (Table 6).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additional concerns about the imputation models remain.
 First, the models fit have a surprisingly high 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 value – 0.8 for rural, and 0.91 for urban areas.
 Such a high 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 value may be suggestive of overfitting.
 The rural model includes as a covariate the natural logarithm of comparable
 meat consumption per adult equivalent, and its square – the coefficients
 for both are positive.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Includes health, a subset of education, clothing, financial services, durables,
 and housing.
 It has a correlation of 0.987 with total consumption and corresponds to
 33.7 percent of consumption as noted by the authors.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The rural model also includes number of items purchased in logarithms,
 where presumably 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

 is treated as 0,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Not explicitly stated in the report.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which can lead to biased coefficients particularly when the proportion
 of 0 is large 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "battese1997note"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The authors include the nat.
 log.
 of hoes owned as well a fishing and hunting gear which likely have multiple
 0.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Finally, the model likely includes many covariates that are potentially
 highly correlated.
 For example, number of tubers consumed from own consumption and purchased.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model for urban areas has an 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 value of 0.91, one of the higher values observed in such an exercise.
 The model includes the number of inactive household members, which a priori
 one would expect to be negatively related to consumption, but is positive
 in this case.
 Moreover, the model suggests that between 2015 and 2022 the number of inactive
 members increased by nearly 1 person, from 1.6 to 2.4.
 Beyond the issue of the inactive members, the urban and rural models share
 many of the same limitations.
 Mainly, the high 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

is suggestive of overfitting that would limit its predictive out-of-sample
 capacity, particularly when applying the model to data that is 7 years
 ahead.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, Zambia’s 2023 poverty estimates underscore the challenges of
 applying S2S imputation in the context of survey design differences and
 extended time gaps.
 While the results provide useful insights, issues related to model assumptions,
 parameter stability, and data representativeness warrant careful consideration.
 This case emphasizes the importance of robust validation and sensitivity
 analyses to ensure reliable estimates when addressing data gaps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To properly understand the limitations of S2S the following section goes
 in-depth into the basics of S2S.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The basics behind survey-to-survey imputation (S2S)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:The-basics-behind"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imputation is a method for filling in missing data.
 According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the first instance of a statistical method to replace a missing value
 dates to 1930,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "allan1930method"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the first widespread use of the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

imputation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 comes from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "madow1983incomplete"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As noted by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The method was originally proposed to fill in missing observations and
 considered the nature of the missing data (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "dempster1977maximum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The goal of the multiple imputation approach is not to create a single
 imputation, but multiple imputations to reflect the uncertainty around
 the actual value.
 Multiple imputation's goal is to create imputations for observations with
 missing data to obtain a valid estimand with adequate confidence intervals
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For example, in the case of a regression on agricultural yields the variable
 capturing plot sizes may have missing values and these must be imputed
 with the aim of not losing information as well as obtaining a valid estimate
 of the coefficient for the relationship between land and yields.
 Using multiple imputation in this example, as opposed to just the predicted
 land size, is expected to reduce the rate of false positives.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The case of a variable that is entirely missing in the dataset was not considere
d by the original multiple imputation literature.
 The academic background for predicting an entirely missing variable in
 a given dataset is more aligned to the small area estimation literature
 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "rao2005small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "rao2015small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Perhaps the first instance of survey-to-survey imputation, as is applied
 in the World Bank, comes from the work of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jesko1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which is more aligned to small area estimation and noted by the authors.
 The key difference to small area estimation up to that point was that 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jesko1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 predicted the variable of interest, consumption, at the household level
 and from that they obtained aggregate statistics based on the prediction
 of consumption.
 Nevertheless, earlier examples exist where data from different sources
 are combined to predict a variable of interest at the household level (for
 example, Arellano and Meghir 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citebyear
key "arellano1992female"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Nevertheless, what is innovative of the work from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jesko1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is that the authors apply models fit on survey data to the census with
 the goal of replicating the entire consumption distribution and from that
 distribution obtain estimates of poverty and other welfare indicators as
 if one had welfare in the census.
 After refinements by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the work became the basis of what later was referred to as poverty mapping
 in the World Bank.
 The key difference between survey-to-survey imputation and small area estimatio
n is that small area estimation aims to replicate the welfare distribution
 for each specific area or group of interest, rather than only for the entire
 population.
 One of the first applications of the methods from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to predict national level poverty can be seen in the work of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "simler2004estimating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who use the methods to track changes in poverty in Mozambique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Survey-to-survey (S2S) imputation for poverty measurement relies on the
 assumption that a population's welfare distribution can be captured by
 a linear model.
 Hence, the assumed data generating process (DGP) for transformed welfare
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Transformed data is often used as the dependent variable to ensure the model's
 assumptions hold.
 For simplicity, throughout this document the assumed transformation is
 the natural logarithm, although many others are possible.
 Meeting the model's statistical assumptions is crucial for reliable estimation.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "corral2022guidelines"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 demonstrate that violations of these assumptions, particularly the normality
 of residuals, can lead to biased poverty estimates.
 Their analysis shows that appropriate transformation of the dependent variable
 (household welfare) can significantly reduce such bias.
 When the standard logarithmic transformation proves insufficient, alternative
 transformations may be necessary to better approximate normality in the
 model's error term.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln\,y_{i}=x_{i}\beta+e_{i};\:e_{i}\sim N(0,\sigma_{e}^{2})\label{eq:welfare model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of independent variables common to the source survey and the
 target survey,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
the source survey is the one used to fit equation 1, and the target survey
 is where the parameters estimated in the source survey are applied to impute
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a random disturbance term that is assumed to be distributed i.i.d.
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N(0,\sigma_{e}^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 as well as the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

 parameters are estimated using the source survey or the training data.
 These estimated parameters are then applied to the target data to predict
 poverty or other welfare related indicators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because normally distributed errors are assumed, for any given household,
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, the probability of being poor is entirely dependent on its expected welfare,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\hat{β},$
\end_inset

 and its error, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

, which is assumed to follow 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\sim N(0,σ_{e}^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{FGT_{0i}}=Φ\,\left(\frac{\ln z-x_{i}\hat{β}}{\hat{σ}{}_{e}}\right)\label{eq:cum prob}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln z$
\end_inset

 is the natural log of the poverty line,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that if the transformation of the dependent variable is not the natural
 logarithm, then this is not valid.
 The poverty line must be transformed in a similar manner as the dependent
 variable.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Φ$
\end_inset

 is the standard normal distribution.
 Consequently, what the method calculates is each household's probability
 of being poor.
 The average probability of being poor across households corresponds to
 the national poverty rate.
 Additionally, because the only thing differing across households in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cum prob"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are the characteristics, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

, a proxy means test (PMT) approach that relies only on 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\beta$
\end_inset

 will yield the same household ranking as the survey-to-survey approach
 if the same model is used for either.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Under a PMT the threshold is chosen at a given percentile of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\beta$
\end_inset

 so that by construction it yields a desidred proportion of people eligible.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The implementation of welfare predictions in the target data can follow
 different approaches.
 The traditional method, grounded in the multiple imputation literature,
 generates several welfare vectors to reflect prediction uncertainty.
 This approach follows what was implemented in poverty mapping through the
 PovMap software (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "zhao2006user"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and is similar to the methodology used in Stata's multiple imputation
 commands ( 
\family typewriter
mi regress
\family default
).
 Under this approach, each imputed welfare vector is generated through a
 three-step process:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{e}^{2*}\sim\hat{\sigma}_{e0}^{2}\frac{\left(n-K\right)}{\chi_{n-K}^{2*}},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta^{*}\sim MVN\left(\hat{\beta}_{0},\widehat{\textrm{vcov}}(\hat{\beta}_{0})\right),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{i}^{*}\stackrel{iid}{\sim}N\left(0,\sigma_{e}^{2*}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, for each imputed vector, a new 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2*}$
\end_inset

 is drawn and that is used to draw 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{*}$
\end_inset

 and a household specific residual, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The multiple imputation simulation approach is not necessarily aligned
 to reducing the prediction mean squared errors (MSE), but as noted by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 the purpose is to minimize the likelihood of false positives, since normally
 the imputed vectors are then used for regression analysis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative approach, derived from the small area estimation literature,
 treats the source survey as the best representation of the true welfare
 distribution.
 Under this method, parameters estimated from the source survey are applied
 directly to the target data through Monte Carlo simulation.
 For straightforward indicators like poverty rates, practitioners can simply
 apply the asymptotic formula for expected values (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cum prob"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent methodological advances have expanded estimation options to include
 machine learning (ML) techniques.
 However, since most ML methods do not make explicit assumptions about error
 term distributions, they cannot directly replicate the multiple imputation
 approach described above.
 Nevertheless, bootstrap-based alternatives exist.
 These were implemented in both PovMap (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "zhao2006user"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and Stata's 
\family typewriter
sae 
\family default
command by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "nguyen2018sae"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This bootstrapping approach has proven particularly valuable for regularized
 regression techniques, as demonstrated by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lucchetti2024application"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 with lasso regression,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://github.com/pcorralrodas/lassopmm
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and could be extended to other ML methods such as gradient boosting, random
 forests, or Bayesian additive regression trees.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Assuming that equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:welfare model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is fit via OLS and ignoring sampling weights, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 will be equal to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\beta}=(X'X)^{-1}X'y\label{eq:b1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
or, replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $X'\beta+e$
\end_inset

, one gets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\beta}=\beta+(X'X)^{-1}X'e\label{eq:b2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Imputing to a contemporaneous survey
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:sametime"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The successful application of survey-to-survey imputation depends on meeting
 several critical preconditions, first outlined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jesko1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and later refined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These preconditions ensure that the fundamental assumption - both surveys
 represent the same underlying population - holds true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Covariate comparability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variables used to predict welfare must be present and measured consistently
 in both source and target surveys.
 This requirement extends beyond simple presence to encompass:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Identical definitions of key variables 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consistent measurement approaches 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Similar survey implementation protocols
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Distribution Alignment
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the method to work effectively, both surveys must present:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Similar distributions of predictor variables 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Comparable moments (means, variances) across key characteristics 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consistent patterns in the relationships between variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, a commonly used predictor like household size must be defined
 uniformly across surveys.
 If one survey counts only members sharing five or more meals per week while
 another uses a different definition, the resulting distributions may differ
 significantly, potentially leading to biased poverty estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Model Assumptions 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reliability of welfare predictions depends critically on meeting the
 model's statistical assumptions, particularly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Normal distribution of residuals, although this can be relaxed as discussed
 in the previous section 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Homoscedasticity of error terms, although this can be relaxed by modeling
 for heteroskedasticity following the methods from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2002micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "harvey1976estimating"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Linear relationships between predictors and welfare
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When these assumptions are violated, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "corral2022guidelines"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provide evidence that appropriate transformations of the dependent variable
 may help achieve normality.
 In cases where transformations prove insufficient, practitioners may draw
 residuals from their empirical distribution, though this requires the assumptio
n of symmetric errors around zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
2.2 Imputing across time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While survey-to-survey (S2S) imputation offers a potential solution for
 missing welfare data, its application across different time periods requires
 particular scrutiny.
 The method's fundamental assumption—that changes in welfare are driven
 solely by changes in observable characteristics while their relationship
 with welfare remains constant—becomes increasingly tenuous as the temporal
 gap widens.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
The Variance Decomposition Challenge
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The core challenge lies in the decomposition of welfare variance into two
 components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The explicable variance captured by the model: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}\left[x\beta\right]$
\end_inset

, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The unexplained random component: (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In well-specified models, the 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 typically ranges from 0.40 to 0.60, meaning that a substantial portion of
 welfare variation remains unexplained.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 statistic represents the proportion of variance explained by the model:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R^{2}=\mathrm{var}\left[x\hat{\beta}\right]/(\mathrm{var}\left[x\hat{\beta}\right]+\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2})
\]

\end_inset

When imputing across time, practitioners must rely on an error distribution
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

) estimated from historical data, implicitly assuming that households with
 similar predicted welfare face the same probability of being poor across
 different time periods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Population-Level Implications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the overall population, poverty estimates depend on:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The distribution of household characteristics in the target period
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The stability of relationships between these characteristics and welfare
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The assumed consistency of unobserved factors affecting welfare
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming log-normality, for the population, poverty is given by: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
FGT_{0}=Φ\,\left(\frac{\ln z-\bar{X}_{new}\hat{\beta}}{\sqrt{\mathrm{var}\left[X_{new}\hat{\beta}\right]+\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}}}\right)\label{eq:var pov}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mathematically, this translates to predictions, for any given poverty line,
 depending on both the mean welfare (
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}_{new}\hat{\beta}$
\end_inset

) and its variation (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}\left[X_{new}\hat{\beta}\right]+\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Sources of Temporal Instability
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several factors can undermine the method's reliability across time:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Structural changes in welfare determinants (e.g., educational convergence)
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sampling differences between surveys 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Policy changes (e.g., new welfare programs) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Economic shocks or systemic changes (e.g., currency reforms)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These implications extend beyond model specification.
 Many S2S applications employ stepwise regression or regularization techniques
 (like lasso or ridge regression) to optimize model fit, often measured
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 While some argue that endogeneity and omitted variable bias are less concerning
 in predictive modeling,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "dang2021poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 note that endogeneity is not a concern.
 An endogenous variable is frequently defined as an explanatory variable
 that may be correlated with the error term (Wooldridge, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citebyear
key "wooldridge2009introductory"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 p88).
 Omitted variables are related as these are correlated to the error term
 and a covariate.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 these issues become particularly problematic when applying models across
 time periods.
 A model trained on data from one year may produce biased estimates when
 used to predict welfare in another year, as both omitted variables and
 endogeneity can significantly impact the model's temporal stability and
 will likely cause biased estimates limiting the usefulness of S2S to predict
 poverty in years where a welfare aggregate is unavailable (see Annex 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ann_ovb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Implications for Inequality Measurement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The challenges extend to inequality measurement.
 The reliance on error distributions obtained from a different point in
 time, particularly affects inequality measurement.
 Under the common assumption of log-normally distributed welfare, the Gini
 coefficient depends critically on the welfare distribution's standard deviation.
 Using an outdated error distribution can thus produce misleading inequality
 estimates, even when mean predictions appear reasonable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that welfare is lognormally distributed then Gini is equal to (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "crow1987lognormal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Gini=2Φ(\frac{σ}{\sqrt{2}})-1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $σ$
\end_inset

 is the standard deviation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, the imputed Gini across time is also dependent on 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{σ}{}_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which is estimated in an older survey since:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
σ^{2}=\mathrm{var}\left[x\beta\right]+\hat{\sigma}{}_{e}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and consequently, also subject to changes in the sample’s distribution of
 the observed characteristics used in the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These limitations suggest that survey-to-survey imputation across time periods
 should be approached with considerable caution, particularly when economic
 conditions or social structures have changed significantly between the
 source and target periods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model Based Simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section some of the aspects discussed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:The-basics-behind"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are explored.
 Mainly the section will rely on simulated data to explore how violations
 of the underlying tenets of survey-to-survey imputation may affect imputed
 poverty estimates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Creating populations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Creating-populations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We create 1,000 populations of 20,000 households where the welfare of the
 population is generated with the following data generating process (DGP):
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln y_{i}=3+0.1x_{1_{i}}+0.5x_{2_{i}}-0.25x_{3_{i}}+0.2x_{4_{i}}-0.15x_{5_{i}}+e_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\sim N(0,0.5^{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a discrete variable, simulated as the rounded integer value of the maximum
 between 1 and a random Poisson variable with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $λ=4$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform number between
 0 and 1 is less than 0.2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform number between
 0 and 1 is less than 0.5 as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=1$
\end_inset

, otherwise it is equal to 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{4}\sim N(2.5,2^{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{5}$
\end_inset

 is a variable drawn from a Student’s t distribution with 5 degrees of freedom
 and scaled by 0.25
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gini for this distribution is 0.38, and the covariates explain roughly
 47 percent of the variation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extracting samples 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Extracting-samples"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under each of the 1,000 populations, take the following samples are taken:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Random sample: a 20 percent simple random sample (SRS) of the population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Bottom biased sample: here, the poorest quintile is purposely undersampled.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For the top 80, take an SRS for each centile, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the bottom 20, take a 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 percent as a sample.
 This means that for the 20th centile an SRS sample of 20% is taken, for
 the 19th centile, 19 percent is sampled, for the 18th centile, 18 percent
 is sampled, and so forth.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Biased sample top and bottom: Create a biased sample, where the poorest
 quintile and the richest quintile are purposely under sampled.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For the top 20, sample 
\begin_inset Formula $100-c$
\end_inset

 percent.
 This means that for the 80th centile, an SRS sample of 20% is taken, for
 the 81st centile a sample of 19 percent is taken, for the 82nd centile,
 18 percent is sampled, and so forth.
 Note that we do not sample the top 1 percent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the bottom 20, we sample 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 percent.
 This means that for the 20th centile an SRS sample of 20% is taken, for
 the 19th centile, 19 percent is sampled, for the 18th centile, 18 percent
 is sampled, and so forth.
 Note that the bottom 1 percent is not sampled.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all other centiles (21-79), an SRS sample by centile is taken.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
How to Impute?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The typical imputation approach undertaken, at least under the S2S work
 done by World Bank staff, follows the literature on multiple imputation.
 A similar approach was followed in the software implementation of small
 area estimation method proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Under the MI approach the parameters estimated on the training data are
 not applied directly to the target data, instead the parameters to be applied
 to the target data are drawn from their posterior distributions as illustrated
 in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:The-basics-behind"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For small area estimation, the approach from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 has been updated to follow the approach from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "molina2010small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Under the method of the latter, the parameters estimated using the training
 data are applied directly to the data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The prediction bias between approaches is minimal across different poverty
 lines (Figure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_eb_mi"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Although applying parameters directly (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Fixed B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) has the lowest bias, the difference between all methods is minuscule and
 in the most biased case in the simulation done here is less than 0.025 percentag
e points.
 Also, the number of imputations performed under MI seems to have little
 if any impact on bias.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bias in FGT0 under MI and direct application of parameters 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:bias_eb_mi"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/WB378870/OneDrive - WBG/S2S_RTM_guidelines/5.figures/mi_ebp_fgt0.jpg
	lyxscale 25
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
Note: Data are generated as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creating-populations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Bias is assessed at various poverty lines across the welfare distribution.
 Specifically, these lines correspond to percentiles that are multiples
 of 5.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A word of caution is warranted here and it is related to how noise is estimated.
 When applying MI methods the noise is typically estimated using Rubin's
 rules 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rubin1987multiple"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Under Rubin's rules the estimated variance is equal to the sum of within-imputa
tion variance, the between imputation variance, and the between imputation
 variance divided by the number of imputations.
 It is important to remember that these methods were developed for regression
 analysis, where a variable with missing observations is imputed and then
 used in a model.
 Rubin's rules are applied here to obtain a valid standard error.
 Estimating the prediction's noise in a similar manner when parameters are
 applied directly risks producing improper imputations.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 notes how keeping 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta s$
\end_inset

 fixed across imputations can lead to improper imputations since the goal
 of MI is not to minimize the MSE.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When keeping 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 fixed as is done by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "molina2010small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 MSEs are estimated following a parametric bootstrap presented by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gonzalez-manteiga2008bootstrap"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This bootstrap procedure is aligned to the model's assumptions under small
 area estimation, but is not necessarily aligned for S2S.
 However, in Annex (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Parametric-Bootstrap-to"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) evidence is presented on how the method can yield estimates of the MSE
 that can be reliable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Re-weighting the sample 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of this section is to test the implications of under-sampling
 segments of the population and then re-weighting to match means.
 Re-weighting is applied by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sinha2022poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for the case of India where there were concerns regarding the sampling
 of the target survey.
 Weights are also frequently recalculated to adjust phone surveys like is
 done in the case of Afghanistan 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barriga2023updating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "zhang2023correcting"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 present how sampling weights were calculated to correct the sampling and
 nonresponse biases of phone surveys.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Although referred to as a max-entropy approach by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sinha2022poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "zhang2023correcting"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the method used to adjust the target sample weights is in reality minimum
 cross-entropy where the sampling weights in the target survey are adjusted
 by the smallest extent possible given the constraints (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "wittenberg2010introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When the original sampling weights of the target survey are ignored, it
 is assumed that every observation had a similar probability of being selected,
 then the re-weighting method is max-entropy (see Golan, Judge and Miller
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "GolanBook"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a more thorough exposition of maximum entropy).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The constraints, in the case of India's imputation, correspond to the mean
 of a set of variables that are found in other nationally representative
 surveys.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To test the problems with under-sampling and re-weighting, two sampling
 scenarios are used as an illustrative example.
 The samples are taken from a population created as described in section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For the re-weighting exercise, three possible re-weighting scenarios are
 considered:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Reweighting is done using Stata's user created command 
\family typewriter
wentropy
\family default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Corral_Rodas_wentropy"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The command is used instead of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wittenberg2010introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\family typewriter
maxentropy
\family default
 command due to 
\family typewriter
wentropy
\family default
 providing solutions to instances where 
\family typewriter
maxentropy
\family default
 fails.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Covariate match: The simple random sample’s mean of each covariate is used
 to calibrate the weights of the biased samples.
 For re-weighting, I use minimum cross-entropy to adjust prior weights by
 the smallest amount possible so that the constraints (i.e., the means) are
 satisfied.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Linear fit match: The linear fit’s mean of the simple random sample is used
 to calibrate the weights of the biased samples.
 Weights are calibrated using minimum cross-entropy to adjust prior weights
 by the smallest amount possible so that the constraints (i.e., the means)
 are satisfied.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Linear fit & variance match: The linear fit’s 
\series bold
mean
\series default
 and 
\series bold
variance
\series default
 of the simple random sample are used to calibrate the weights of the biased
 samples.
 Weights are calibrated using minimum cross-entropy to adjust prior weights
 by the smallest amount possible so that the constraints (i.e., the mean and
 the variance of the linear fit) are satisfied.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since the simulated data does not have sampling weights, the priors are
 equal to 1 and thus minimum cross-entropy is in reality max-entropy in
 this instance.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Standardizing covariates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basics of standardizing covariates is simple.
 In principle, from the data where the model is fit (source data)the mean
 and variance of each covariate is known.
 Consequently, covariates in the sample to be imputed (target data) can
 be adjusted so that the mean and variance of the covariates are aligned
 to that of the source data.
 This is what 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dang2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 recommend for making different survey samples more comparable.
 However, a key assumption here is that the covariates follow a normal distribut
ion.
 In tests done by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dang2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 with data from Jordan the method is judged to be valid.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To test the validity of covariate standardization, the same samples detailed
 in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are used.
 Note, however, that the covariates here do not follow a normal distribution.
 Covariate standardization is done by adjusting the covariate from the 
\begin_inset Formula $new$
\end_inset

 survey in the following manner:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{new}=(x_{new}-\hat{\mu}_{x_{new}})\frac{\hat{\sigma}_{x}}{\hat{\sigma}_{x_{new}}}+\hat{\mu}_{x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Results
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Results_simdata"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To remove the potential for other sources of bias, instead of refitting
 a model on the sample, the actual values for the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and the error distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are used.
 For each sample, under each population, 100 vectors in the sample are created
 by adding the linear fit to a randomly drawn error term 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\sim N(0,0.5^{2})$
\end_inset

 to every observation.
 Then, poverty and Gini estimates are obtained for each of the 100 created
 vectors using the newly created survey weights or the standardized covariates
 to calculate poverty and Gini for the samples.
 The average value of the 100 Gini and poverty estimates is used as the
 final estimate.
 Bias is calculated for each measure of interest by comparing the estimate
 with the actual value from the population.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If left unadjusted, poverty estimates under the bottom biased samples will
 underestimate poverty across the entire welfare distribution (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_reweight"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Attempts to correct the bias via the creation of weights that match the
 means of the model covariates (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Match X
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) do not have any impact on the bias.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since the weights assume no priors, these are in fact calculated using maximum
 entropy.
 When prior weights are considered the method adjusts the existing weights
 by the smallest possible amount to ensure the constraints match, this is
 known as cross-entropy.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Adjusting weights so that the covariate means and variances match also
 seems to have little impact on the bias (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Match X and var[X]
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 However, adjusting weights so that the mean linear fit of the target data
 matches the average of the linear fit of the model (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

) leads to considerably better results (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Match XB and var[XB]
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Similarly, much better results are achieved by standardizing each covariate
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Standardize each X
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, as well as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Standardizing XB
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The latter achieves a similar result to adjusting weights so that the mean
 of the linear fit and its variance matches that of the training data.
 In principle, both methods are attempting to achieve the same thing.
 The results presented here are related to Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:var pov"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, thus what matters for poverty is not just the mean of the linear fit,
 it is also dependent on the variance of the linear fit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar performance of the different adjustment methods is observed when
 applying these to top and bottom biased samples (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_reweight-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 An interesting outcome in these results is that if the model were only
 judged at the 40th percentile (i.e.
 at a threshold that yields a poverty rate of 40 percent) it would ignore
 the biased nature of the samples.
 For this reason, it is always recommended to check results across the entire
 welfare distribution, like is done here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results show that standardizing covariates as suggested by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dang2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 may be just as good or a better approach than reweighting covariates, of
 course this result may not hold under different covariates.
 However, even better results are obtained by standardizing the linear fit
 (
\begin_inset Formula $X\beta)$
\end_inset

.
 Standardizing 
\begin_inset Formula $X\beta$
\end_inset

 yields phenomenal results under both biased samples tested.
 Given that the standardizing relies on normally distributed data, perhaps
 a better option may be achieved from reweighting in other scenarios.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Results presented in Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_reweight"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_reweight-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 suggest that not all types of reweighting work well.
 Re-weighting to match means, as done in an application in India by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sinha2022poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, still yields biased results.
 Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

 used are always the true values, one can surmise that the bias from the
 sampling cannot be overcome by simply reweighting the data.
 This also holds true for cases where the weights are adjusted so that the
 linear fit in the biased sample matches the mean of the SRS data.
 This sampling bias will be in addition to any other potential sources of
 bias, for example, non-normally distributed residuals or using a 
\begin_inset Formula $σ_{e}$
\end_inset

 that does not correspond to the same period.
 The bias is in addition to all the other potential sources of bias of the
 imputation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bias in FGT0 under bottom biased samples (Sec 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and different correction measures 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:bias_reweight"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/WB378870/OneDrive - WBG/S2S_RTM_guidelines/5.figures/weights_std_bb_fgt0.jpg
	lyxscale 25
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
