\end_inset

.
 Bias is assessed at various poverty lines across the welfare distribution.
 Specifically, these lines correspond to percentiles that are multiples
 of 5.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For Gini, a similar issue is at play.
 Because biasing a sample by excluding households at the bottom of the distribut
ion will likely lead to lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}[xβ]$
\end_inset

, which is not addressed by the re-weighting procedure used, keeping everything
 else equal leads to a downward biased estimate of Gini (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_reweight-gini"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 This is worse under the top and bottom biased samples because the value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}[x\beta]$
\end_inset

 is considerably smaller than under the bottom biased sample (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_reweight-gini-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Consequently, adjusting the weights so that not just the mean of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\beta$
\end_inset

 matches the value observed in the SRS but also 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}[xβ]$
\end_inset

 yields much better imputed values for Gini.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bias in Gini under bottom biased samples (Sec 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and different correction measures 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
